</table>
<p>The <b>Shan language</b> (<strong class="selflink">Shan</strong>: <span lang="shn" xml:lang="shn"><a href="/wiki/File:Shan-liktai.png" class="image"><font face="Parabaik,Myanmar3,Myanmar2,Myanmar1,MyMyanmar"><img alt="Shan-liktai.png" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/af/Shan-liktai.png/40px-Shan-liktai.png" width="40" height="14" /></font></a></span>, <small>IPA:&#160;</small><span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[lɪ̀k tɑ́ɪ]</a></span> or <span style="font-family:Padauk, Parabaik, Myanmar3, Myanmar2, Myanmar1, MyMyanmar, Thanlwin, Masterpiece Uni Sans">ၽႃႇသႃႇတႆး</span>, <span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA" title="Wikipedia:IPA">[pʰàː sʰàː tái]</a></span>; <a href="/wiki/Burmese_language" title="Burmese language">Burmese</a>: <span lang="my" xml:lang="my"><span style="font-family:Padauk, Parabaik, Myanmar3, Myanmar2, Myanmar1, MyMyanmar, Thanlwin, Masterpiece Uni Sans">ရှမ်းဘာသာ</span></span>, <span title="Pronunciation in IPA" class="IPA"><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:IPA_for_Burmese" title="Wikipedia:IPA for Burmese">[ʃáɴ bàðà]</a></span>; <a href="/wiki/Thai_language" title="Thai language">Thai</a>: <span lang="th" xml:lang="th">ภาษาไทใหญ่</span>) is the native language of <a href="/wiki/Shan_people" title="Shan people">Shan people</a> and spoken mostly in <a href="/wiki/Shan_State" title="Shan State">Shan State</a>, <a href="/wiki/Myanmar" title="Myanmar" class="mw-redirect">Myanmar</a>. It is also used in pockets of <a href="/wiki/Kachin_State" title="Kachin State">Kachin State</a> in Myanmar, in <a href="/wiki/Northern_Thailand" title="Northern Thailand">northern Thailand</a>, and in <a href="/wiki/Xishuangbanna_Dai_Autonomous_Prefecture" title="Xishuangbanna Dai Autonomous Prefecture">Xishuangbanna Dai Autonomous Prefecture</a>, <a href="/wiki/Yunnan_Province" title="Yunnan Province" class="mw-redirect">Yunnan Province</a>, <a href="/wiki/PRC" title="PRC" class="mw-redirect">China</a>. Shan is a member of the <a href="/wiki/Tai-Kadai_languages" title="Tai-Kadai languages">Tai-Kadai language family</a>, and is related to <a href="/wiki/Thai_language" title="Thai language">Thai</a>. It has five tones, which do not correspond exactly to Thai tones, plus a "sixth tone" used for emphasis. It is called <i>Tai-Yai</i>, or <i>Tai Long</i> in the Tai languages. The term "Shan" is an <a href="/wiki/Exonym" title="Exonym" class="mw-redirect">exonym</a> believed to be a Burmese derivative of "Siam".</p>
<p>The number of Shan speakers is not known in part because that of the Shan population is unknown. Estimates of Shan people range from four million to 30 million, though the true number is somewhere around six million, with about half speaking the Shan language; 3.3 million is the number generally estimated.<sup class="Template-Fact" title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from February 2010" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="/wiki/Wikipedia:Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed">citation needed</a></i>]</sup> Many Shan speak local dialects as well as the language of their trading partners. Due to the <a href="/wiki/Internal_conflict_in_Burma" title="Internal conflict in Burma">civil war in Myanmar</a>, few Shan today can read or write in <a href="/w/index.php?title=Shan_script&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Shan script (page does not exist)">Shan script</a>, which was derived from the <a href="/wiki/Burmese_script" title="Burmese script">Burmese script</a>.</p>
